                      <span>2005-03-29</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Not much to add to the landslide of previous reviews. I loved this book, as well as its companion on TR's early years. 
<br />
<br />As I was a bit puzzled by some of the previous negative reviews, I looked at those separately, and would note that many of them refer to the audio version.  Perhaps this is a book that works better on the page, than read aloud.
<br />
<br />In any case, the episodes in TR's life have become almost legendary. Morris tells the stories in a lively way, with a constant forward momentum, unslowed by his ready eye for sympathetic personal anecdotes.  Contrary to a few previous reviews, I did not find the book overly long, much less dull.  
<br />
<br />Reading these books alongside TR's Autobiography worked well for me. It helps that the books are copiously referenced. 
<br />
<br />I can't resist the urge to write "Bully" and "Deee-lighted" here myself!  I eagerly await the third volume.  </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">The Right Man for the Job</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>4</span>
                      /
                      <span>4</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-03-19</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>It is difficult to imagine how different the world would be now if not for Theodore Roosevelt.  He was driven by a moral certitude which may have disappeared forever from the American political landscape, and he changed the country and the world for the better.  When concensus proved impossible, he forced his will through, reforming the essense of Americanism.  See the last two pages for Edmund Morris's lengthy catalog of the achievements of Roosevelt's administration, and try to imagine how he achieved them, mostly in the face of implacable opposition.  Morris's book is scholarly, yet accessible, and every one of it's 555 pages of text is entertaining.  For instance, in the course of this history book, you will learn how the Teddy Bear came to be named.  This story of eight years in the making of America will make you proud.</span>
                  
              
